Label: XML_FIXED_LINE
Comment: "Fixed Telephony (ATM/IP) and Fixed Wireless phone numbers are supported here."

Label: XML_UAN
Comment: "Call Centres, CENTREX and Direct Inward Dialling (DID) prefixes have been added under\nuan."

Label: XML_TOLL_FREE
Comment: "242 300 is a Domestic Toll Free service."

Label: XML_UAN
Comment: "225[0-46-9] ranges are mentioned as DID (Direct Inward Dialing) numbers in ITU doc.\nhttp://whatis.techtarget.com/definition/Direct-Inward-Dialing-DID. Found valid numbers\nonline."

Label: SC
Comment: "Excluding local normal numbers from the general description (and indeed from being possible\nshort numbers, since they definitely are not)."

Label: SC_CARRIER_SPECIFIC
Comment: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/6-1-1 says it is only partially supported, similar to\narticles on these other numbers. 7-1-1 is required to be supported by all carriers in\nthe US, but in Canada it is up to individual communities it seems."

Label: SC_SMS_SERVICES
Comment: "We also support so-called ""long codes"" (8 digits). Technically we know that 30000 is\nnot a valid short-code but this is too complex/not worth the time to exclude here."

Label: XML_UAN
Comment: "Prefix 310 (7 digit) is added based on user report and online documents."

Label: XML_VOIP
Comment: "600 (Canadian Non-Geographic Tariffed Services) are satellite numbers as per Wikipedia:\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_code_600"

Label: XML_MOBILE
Comment: "Adding 61[237], 285 and 295 since online numbers have been found with this prefix."

Label: XML_FIXED_LINE
Comment: "The ITU data seems to be somewhat incomplete. We ensure that the fully-specified mobile\nprefixes in the document are classified as such by excluding them from the fixed-line\nranges, but other than this have a generic rule."

Label: XML_MOBILE
Comment: "We assume mobile phone numbers to be the same as fixed-line - further info unavailable"

Label: XML_FIXED_LINE
Comment: "Numbers have been found online for ranges 613, 62x, 63x, 656, 66[2-589]."

Label: XML_MOBILE
Comment:
"Adding 27, 28, 299, 31, 508 and 566 as extra prefixes, as they have been found to be
valid by sending SMSs and looking at online number lookup sites. Numbers have been
found online for the following ranges 258, 26x, 29x, 53x, 54x, 55x, 56x. Most have
mobile numbers online so we have put them under mobile but is possible they are a
mixture of fixed line and mobile."

Label: XML_FIXED_LINE
Comment: "Adding the 869 302 prefix as it is used by Marriott Hotels, even though no other record\nof it can be found."

Label: XML_MOBILE
Comment: "Added some more prefixes in the 66 and 76 range from online numbers."

Label: XML_FIXED_LINE
Comment: "The 800 NXX code is listed as being ""national only"", but we successfully reached numbers\nfrom Switzerland with this prefix so do not list it as noInternationalDialling."

Label: XML_FIXED_LINE
Comment: "The Westtel numbers in the plan seem now to be live and assigned to fixed-line phones,\nas per numbers found online and their website http://www.logic.ky."

Label: XML_MOBILE
Comment: "Adding central office codes 576, 923 and 936 from numbers found online.\nMost central office codes that were surrendered have not been included, with the\nexception of 546 where numbers have been found."

"http://barbados.usembassy.gov/emergency-st_lucia.html
http://www.stlucia.org/planner/travel.asp
Note the second source only mentions 911, so we are not sure if 999 is indeed an
emergency number here."

Label: XML_FIXED_LINE
Comment: "Adding 430 since numbers have been found with these prefixes online."

Comment:
"Extra exchange codes 232, 289, 355, 472, 633, 637, 646, 647, 649, 653, 687, 734 and 828
were seen in the white and yellow pages, but no numbers with these exchange codes have

Label: XML_MOBILE

Label: XML_FIXED_LINE

Label: XML_MOBILE
Comment:
"We support below mobile ranges additionally which are not listed in ITU doc.
- 270: Found valid numbers online.
- 26[6-9] and 48[5-9]: Evidence from bmobile.
- 70[1-9]: Official TATT doc."

Label: SC_CARRIER_SPECIFIC
Comment: "https://support.google.com/plus/answer/1304917\n611 is listed as working from ""most"" wireless carriers. 211 has complete coverage\nonly in 38 states."

Label: SC_STANDARD_RATE
Comment: "29002 is standard rate as per test results."

Label: XML
Comment:
"Note the national prefix of US is the same as its country code, and when formatting phone
numbers in the national format, it is not included. Therefore, we omit it here to make
formatting consistent with the rest of the world. The same applies to all the
countries/regions under NANPA"

Label: XML
Comment: "The national prefix of ""1"" here is the same as the country code. It is not used by default\nwhen formatting, but is set here so that users who are calling formatByPattern can specify\nNationalPrefixFormattingRule if they want to."

Label: XML_UAN
Comment: "710 range is assigned to federal government of the US. As these are service numbers\n(non geographical) supporting them here."

Label: XML_FIXED_LINE
Comment: "For 570, 571 and 572 prefixes, we believe the ITU doc incorrectly listed them to be under\narea code 758, which should be 784."

Label: XML_MOBILE
Comment: "Supported 49[67] XXXX mobile ranges based on user report."

Label: XML_MOBILE
